\end{gathered}
$$

The probability of \( n \rightarrow \bar{n} \) at time \( t \) is \(\sin ^{2} \frac{\alpha t}{\hbar}\).

problem:
A helium atom contains two electrons, each with a charge of \(-e\), and a nuclear charge of \(2e\). Calculate the ground state energy of the helium atom, assuming the most probable radius is \(r \sim R\), and using the following averages:
\[
\left\langle \frac{1}{r_1} \right\rangle = \left\langle \frac{1}{r_2} \right\rangle \approx \frac{1}{R}, \quad \left\langle \frac{1}{r_{12}} \right\rangle \approx \frac{1}{2R}
\]
According to the uncertainty principle, we have:
\[
\left\langle \boldsymbol{p}_1^2 \right\rangle = \left\langle \boldsymbol{p}_2^2 \right\rangle \approx \frac{\hbar^2}{R^2}
\]
and utilizing the following total energy operator:
\begin{equation*}
H = \frac{1}{2m} \left(p_1^2 + p_2^2\right) - 2e^2 \left(\frac{1}{r_1} + \frac{1}{r_2}\right) + \frac{e^2}{r_{12}}
\end{equation*}

solution:
The final expression is a superposition of $\psi(t)$ with the eigenstates of $\hat{A}$. Thus, the expectation value of $\hat{A}$ is clearly

\begin{equation*}
\langle\hat{A}\rangle=\left|C_{1}\right|^{2} a_{1}+\left|C_{2}\right|^{2} a_{2} \tag{3}
\end{equation*}

From the equality of equations (1) and (2), we have

$$
C_{1}+C_{2}=\exp \left(-\mathrm{i} \omega_{1} t\right), \quad C_{1}-C_{2}=\exp \left(-\mathrm{i} \omega_{2} t\right)
$$

Therefore, we have

\begin{align*}
& C_{1}=\frac{1}{2}\left[\exp \left(-\mathrm{i} \omega_{1} t\right)+\exp \left(-\mathrm{i} \omega_{2} t\right)\right], \quad C_{2}=\frac{1}{2}\left[\exp \left(-\mathrm{i} \omega_{1} t\right)-\exp \left(-\mathrm{i} \omega_{2} t\right)\right] \\
& \left|C_{1}\right|^{2}=\frac{1}{2}\left[1+\cos \left(\omega_{1}-\omega_{2}\right) t\right], \quad\left|C_{2}\right|^{2}=\frac{1}{2}\left[1-\cos \left(\omega_{1}-\omega_{2}\right) t\right] \tag{4}
\end{align*}

Substituting equation (4) into equation (3) gives

$$
\langle\hat{A}\rangle=\frac{a_{1}+a_{2}}{2}+\frac{a_{1}-a_{2}}{2} \cos \frac{\left(E_{1}-E_{2}\right) t}{\hbar}
$$

