In the regions $x<0$ and $x>a$, $\psi(x)=0$. In the region $0<x<a$, $\psi(x)$ satisfies the equation

\begin{equation*}
-\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2 \mu} \cdot \frac{\mathrm{d}^{2} \psi(x)}{\mathrm{d} x^{2}}+\alpha \delta\left(x-\frac{a}{2}\right) \psi(x)=E \psi(x) \tag{1}
\end{equation*}

and the conditions

\begin{gather*}
\psi(0)=0, \quad \psi(a)=0, \quad \psi\left(\frac{a^{+}}{2}\right)=\psi\left(\frac{a^{-}}{2}\right) \tag{2} \\
\psi^{\prime}\left(\frac{a^{+}}{2}\right)-\psi^{\prime}\left(\frac{a^{-}}{2}\right)=\frac{2 \mu \alpha}{\hbar^{2}} \psi\left(\frac{a}{2}\right) \tag{3}
\end{gather*}

The general solution to equation (1) is

\[
\begin{array}{ll}
\psi_{1}(x)=A \sin \left(k x+\varphi_{1}\right), & 0<x<a / 2 \\
\psi_{2}(x)=B \sin \left(k x+\varphi_{2}\right), & a / 2<x<a \tag{4}
\end{array}
\]

where $k=\sqrt{\frac{2 \mu E}{\hbar^{2}}}$. If $\alpha=0$, then $V(x)$ becomes an infinite square well of width $a$. In this case, condition (3) becomes

\begin{equation*}
\psi^{\prime}\left(\frac{a^{+}}{2}\right)-\psi^{\prime}\left(\frac{a^{-}}{2}\right)=0 \tag{5}
\end{equation*}

For the infinite square well with $\alpha=0$, the general solution for the wave function is also form (4), but the wave function must satisfy conditions (2) and (5). The only difference between the cases $\alpha=0$ and $\alpha \neq 0$ is that the value of $\psi^{\prime}(x)$ at $x=a / 2$ in the wave function is 0, so for $\alpha \neq 0$, condition (3) turns into condition (5), meaning $\psi^{\prime}(x)$ is continuous at $x=a / 2$. Such wave functions are stationary state wave functions for both potential wells. We can check the stationary state wave function of an infinite square well

$$
\psi_{n}(x)=\sqrt{\frac{2}{a}} \sin \frac{n \pi x}{a}, \quad n=1,2,3, \cdots
$$

to see if any satisfy the condition $\psi_{n}(a / 2)=0$. Clearly, $\psi_{n}(x)$ for $n=2,4,6, \cdots$ satisfies this condition, and they are also stationary state wave functions for the potential well with $\alpha \neq 0$. Thus, part of the solution to this problem is

$$
\psi_{n}(x)=\sqrt{\frac{2}{a}} \sin \frac{n \pi x}{a}, \quad E_{n}=\frac{n^{2} \pi^{2} \hbar^{2}}{2 \mu a^{2}}, \quad n=2,4, \cdots
$$

Another part of the solution is obtained from the general solution (4) of equation (1) and conditions (2), and (3). Substituting (4) into condition (3) yields $\varphi_{1}=0, \varphi_{2}=-k a, B=-A$. Thus,

\begin{align*}
& \psi_{1}(x)=A \sin k x, \quad 0<x<a / 2 \\
& \psi_{2}(x)=-A \sin k(x-a), \quad a / 2<x<a \tag{6}
\end{align*}

Substituting (6) into condition (3) gives

\begin{equation*}
-k \cot \frac{k a}{2}=\frac{\mu \alpha}{\hbar^{2}} \tag{7}
\end{equation*}

Let

$$
\xi=\frac{k a}{2}, \quad Q=\frac{\mu \alpha a}{2 \hbar^{2}} \quad \text{(constant)}
$$

Equation (7) becomes

$$
-\xi \cot \xi=Q
$$

The stationary state energy $E^{\prime}$ is determined by the intersection points $\xi_{i}(i=1,2, \cdots)$ of the curve $y_{1}=-\xi \cot \xi$ and the line $y_{2}=Q$.

The lowest energy is $E_{1}^{\prime}=\frac{2 \xi_{1}^{2} \hbar^{2}}{\mu a^{2}}$.

Since

$$
\frac{\pi}{2}<\xi_{1}<\pi
$$

Thus,

$$
\frac{\pi^{2} \hbar^{2}}{2 \mu a^{2}}<E_{1}^{\prime}<\frac{2 \pi^{2} \hbar^{2}}{\mu a^{2}}
$$

The lowest energy in the first group is $E_{2}=\frac{2 \pi^{2} \hbar^{2}}{\mu a^{2}}$. Therefore, the ground state energy of the system is $E_{1}^{\prime}$, and the first excited state energy is $E_{2}$.

