problem:
Describe the lower energy states of a hydrogen molecule, and provide the approximate energy values of the excited states.

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{ccc}
Deuterium: $0(\mathrm{eV})$, & $0.89(\mathrm{eV})$, & $2.96(\mathrm{eV})$ \\
$J: 0$ & 2 & 4 \\
Protium: $0.30(\mathrm{eV})$, & $1.78(\mathrm{eV})$, & $4.46(\mathrm{eV})$ \\
$J: 1$ & 3 & 5 \\
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

solution:
According to the first-order time-dependent perturbation theory, if a time-dependent perturbation Hamiltonian $H^{(1)}$ acts on the system at $t=0$, and the system's initial state is $|k\rangle$ with corresponding eigenenergy $E_{k}$, then the probability of a transition to the state $|j\rangle$ with energy $E_{j}$ at time $t$ is given by $\left|C_{j}\right|^{2}$, where

\begin{equation*}
C_{j}=\frac{1}{\mathrm{i} \hbar} \int_{0}^{t} \langle j| H^{(1)}\left(t^{\prime}\right)|k\rangle \exp \left(\mathrm{i} \omega t^{\prime}\right) \mathrm{d} t^{\prime}, \quad \hbar \omega=E_{j}-E_{k} \tag{1}
\end{equation*}

In this problem, we have

$$
H^{(1)}\left(t^{\prime}\right)=e \varepsilon_{0} z \exp \left(-t^{\prime} / \tau\right), \quad t^{\prime}>0
$$

where the direction of the electric field is along the $z$-axis. As $t \rightarrow \infty$, equation (1) becomes

$$
C_{j}=\frac{e \varepsilon_{0}}{\mathrm{i} \hbar}\langle j| z|k\rangle \int_{0}^{\infty} \exp \left[\left(\mathrm{i} \omega-\frac{1}{\tau}\right) t^{\prime}\right] \mathrm{d} t^{\prime}
$$

Since the time integral is

$$
\int_{0}^{\infty} \exp \left[\left(\mathrm{i} \omega-\frac{1}{\tau}\right) t^{\prime}\right] \mathrm{d} t^{\prime} = \frac{1}{\mathrm{i} \omega-\frac{1}{\tau}}\left[\exp \left(\left(\mathrm{i} \omega-\frac{1}{\tau}\right) t^{\prime}\right)\right]_{0}^{\infty} = -\frac{1}{\mathrm{i} \omega-\frac{1}{\tau}}
$$

Therefore,

\begin{equation*}
C_{j} = \frac{e \varepsilon_{0}}{\hbar(\omega+\mathrm{i} / \tau)}\langle j| z|k\rangle \tag{2}
\end{equation*}

Let $|k\rangle$ be the ground state $u_{100}$, and $|j\rangle$ be the 2p state $u_{210}$, then

$$
\langle j| z|k\rangle = \int_{\text{whole space}} u_{210}^{*} r \cos \theta u_{100} \mathrm{~d} V
$$

Substitute

$$
\left\{\begin{array}{l}
u_{100} = R_{10} Y_{00} = \frac{2}{\sqrt{4 \pi}} \cdot \frac{1}{a_{0}^{3 / 2}} \exp \left(-\frac{r}{a_{0}}\right) \\
u_{210} = R_{21} Y_{10} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{4 \pi}} \cdot \frac{1}{\left(2 a_{0}\right)^{3 / 2}} \frac{r}{a_{0}} \exp \left(-\frac{r}{2 a_{0}}\right) \cos \theta
\end{array}\right.
$$

into equation (2), then we have

\begin{align*}
\langle j| z|k\rangle & = \frac{1}{2^{3 / 2}} \cdot \frac{1}{a_{0}^{4}} \int_{0}^{\infty} r^{4} \exp \left(-\frac{3 r}{2 a_{0}}\right) \mathrm{d} r \int_{0}^{\pi} \cos^{2} \theta \sin \theta \mathrm{~d} \theta \\
& = \frac{4!}{2^{3 / 2}}\left(\frac{2}{3}\right)^{6} a_{0} \tag{3}
\end{align*}

(The formula $\int_{0}^{\infty} r^{4} \exp (-\beta r) \mathrm{d} r = \frac{4!}{\beta^{5}}$ is used above.) Substituting equation (3) into equation (2), the transition probability is finally calculated as

$$
P = \left|C_{j}\right|^{2} = \frac{2^{15}}{3^{10}} \cdot \frac{a_{0}^{2} e^{2} \varepsilon_{0}^{2}}{\hbar^{2}\left(\omega^{2}+1 / \tau^{2}\right)}
$$

problem:
