problem:
A beam of particles with mass \( m \) and momentum \( p=\hbar k \) is incident from \( x=-\infty \) and is affected by a periodic \(\delta\) potential

\[
V(x)=V_{0} \sum_{n=0}^{\infty} \delta(x-n a), \quad a>0
\]

Assume \(x<0\), and given equation (4),

\begin{equation*}
\psi(x)=\left[A+\mathrm{i} \frac{m V_{0}}{2 \hbar^{2} k} \sum_{n} \psi(n a) \mathrm{e}^{-\mathrm{i} n a k}\right] \mathrm{e}^{\mathrm{i} k x}+2 B \mathrm{e}^{-\mathrm{i} k x} \tag{6}
\end{equation*}

derive the condition for total reflection.

solution:
**Solution Method 1:** When \( x < 0 \), the wave function remains in the form as in equation (1). For \( 0 < x < t \), the Schrödinger equation is

\[
-\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2m} \nabla^{2} \psi = 0
\]

If \( \psi \) takes the form: \( \mathrm{e}^{\mathrm{i} k_{y} \cdot y} \cdot \mathrm{e}^{k x} \), then

\[
-k^{\prime 2} + k^{2} = 0, \quad k = \pm k^{\prime}
\]

Thus, the wave function for \( 0 < x < t \) is

\[
\psi_{2}(x, y) = \left(a \mathrm{e}^{k^{\prime} x} + b \mathrm{e}^{-k^{\prime} x}\right) \mathrm{e}^{i k_{y} \cdot y}
\]

Overall, we have

\[
\begin{array}{ll}
x < 0, & \psi_{1}(x) = \mathrm{e}^{\mathrm{i} k_{x} x} + r \mathrm{e}^{-\mathrm{i} k_{x} x} \\
0 < x < t, & \psi_{2}(x) = a \mathrm{e}^{k^{\prime} x} + b \mathrm{e}^{-k^{\prime} x} \\
x > t, & \psi_{3}(x) = c \mathrm{e}^{\mathrm{i} k_{x} x}
\end{array}
\]

Where

\[
k_{x} = \sqrt{\frac{2mE}{\hbar^{2}}} \cos \theta, \quad k^{\prime} = \sqrt{\frac{2mE}{\hbar^{2}}} \sin \theta
\]

Only the \( x \) component is written here. The \( y \) component is simply \( \mathrm{e}^{\mathrm{i} k_{y} \cdot y} \).

\[
k_{y} = \sqrt{\frac{2mE}{\hbar^{2}}} \sin \theta
\]

All boundary conditions are

\[
\begin{gathered}
\left\{
\begin{array}{l}
1+r = a+b \\
\mathrm{i} k_{x}(1-r) = k^{\prime}(a-b) \\
c \mathrm{e}^{\mathrm{i} k_{x} t} = a \mathrm{e}^{k^{\prime} t} + b \mathrm{e}^{-k^{\prime} t}
\end{array}
\right. \\
\mathrm{i} k_{x} \cdot c \mathrm{e}^{\mathrm{i} k_{x} t} = k^{\prime} a \mathrm{e}^{k^{\prime} t} - k^{\prime} b \mathrm{e}^{-k^{\prime} t}
\end{gathered}
\]

Solving, we have

\[
\begin{gathered}
r = \frac{\mathrm{e}^{2 k^{\prime} t} - 1}{1 - \beta^{2} \mathrm{e}^{2 k^{\prime} t}}, \quad \beta = \frac{k^{\prime} - \mathrm{i} k_{x}}{k^{\prime} + \mathrm{i} k_{x}} \\
|R|^{2} = |r|^{2} = \frac{\mathrm{e}^{2 k^{\prime} t} + \mathrm{e}^{-2 k^{\prime} t} - 2}{\mathrm{e}^{2 k^{\prime} t} + \mathrm{e}^{-2 k^{\prime} t} - 2 \cos 4 \theta}
\end{gathered}
\]

**Solution Method 2:** The problem can also be solved by using the method of amplitude superposition, similar to the case of a Fabry-Perot interferometer in optics.

Only considering the \( x \) component, let \( T_{12}, R_{12} \) represent the amplitude transmission and reflection coefficients for the wave from medium 1 to medium 2 respectively. Let \( T_{21}, R_{21} \) represent the amplitude transmission and reflection coefficients for the wave from medium 2 to medium 1 respectively. Given that the incident wave amplitude is 1, the amplitude of the wave emerging from medium 2 is

\[
\begin{aligned}
T & = T_{12} \mathrm{e}^{-\delta} \cdot T_{21} + T_{12} \mathrm{e}^{-\delta} \cdot R_{21} \mathrm{e}^{-2\delta} R_{21} \cdot T_{21} + T_{12} \mathrm{e}^{-\delta} \cdot \left(R_{21} \mathrm{e}^{-2\delta} R_{21}\right)^{2} \cdot T_{21} + \cdots \\
& = T_{12} \mathrm{e}^{-\delta} T_{21} \left[1 + R_{21}^{2} \mathrm{e}^{-2\delta} + \left(R_{21}^{2} \mathrm{e}^{-2\delta}\right)^{2} + \cdots\right] = T_{12} T_{21} \mathrm{e}^{-\delta} \frac{1}{1 - R_{21}^{2} \mathrm{e}^{-2\delta}}
\end{aligned}
\]

Where \( \mathrm{e}^{-\delta} \) is the attenuation coefficient of the wave traveling from one interface to the other in medium 2.

\[
\delta = k^{\prime} t, \quad k^{\prime} = \sqrt{2mE(1 - \cos^{2} \theta)} / \hbar = \sqrt{2mE} \sin \theta / \hbar
\]

Using the result from (1)

\[
R_{12} = \left(k_{1 x} - k_{2 x}\right) / \left(k_{1 x} + k_{2 x}\right), \quad T_{12} = 1 + R_{12} = 2 k_{1} / \left(k_{1 x} + k_{2 x}\right)
\]

However,

\[
\begin{aligned}
& k_{1 x} = \sqrt{2mE} \cos \theta / \hbar \\
& k_{2 x} = \mathrm{i} k^{\prime} = \mathrm{i} \sqrt{2mE} \sin \theta / \hbar
\end{aligned}
\]

So,

\[
\begin{aligned}
& T_{12} = \frac{2 k_{1 x}}{k_{1 x} + k_{2 x}} = \frac{2 \cos \theta}{\cos \theta + \mathrm{i} \sin \theta} = 2 \cos \theta \mathrm{e}^{-\mathrm{i} \theta} \\
& T_{21} = \frac{2 k_{2 x}}{k_{1 x} + k_{2 x}} = \frac{2 \sin \theta}{\cos \theta + \mathrm{i} \sin \theta} = 2 \mathrm{i} \sin \theta \mathrm{e}^{-\mathrm{i} \theta}
\end{aligned}
\]

\[
R_{21} = \frac{k_{2 x} - k_{1 x}}{k_{1 x} + k_{2 x}} = \frac{\mathrm{i} \sin \theta - \cos \theta}{\mathrm{i} \sin \theta + \cos \theta} = \mathrm{e}^{-2 \mathrm{i} \theta}
\]

Thus,

\[
\begin{aligned}
T & = T_{12} T_{21} \mathrm{e}^{-\delta} \frac{1}{1 - R_{21}^{2} \mathrm{e}^{-2\delta}} \\
& = \frac{4 \mathrm{i} \cos \theta \sin \theta \mathrm{e}^{-2 \mathrm{i} \theta} \cdot \mathrm{e}^{-k^{\prime} t}}{1 - \mathrm{e}^{-4 \mathrm{i} \theta} \mathrm{e}^{-2 k^{\prime} t}} \\
& = \frac{2 \mathrm{i} \sin 2 \theta \mathrm{e}^{-2 \mathrm{i} \theta} \mathrm{e}^{-k^{\prime} t}}{1 - \mathrm{e}^{-4 \mathrm{i} \theta} \mathrm{e}^{-2 k^{\prime} t}}
\end{aligned}
\]

Transmittance

\[
\begin{aligned}
|T|^{2} & = \frac{4 \sin^{2} 2 \theta \mathrm{e}^{-2 k^{\prime} t}}{\left(1 - \mathrm{e}^{-2 k^{\prime} t} \cos 4 \theta\right)^{2} + \left(\mathrm{e}^{-2 k^{\prime} t} \sin 4 \theta\right)^{2}} \\
& = \frac{4 \sin^{2} 2 \theta \mathrm{e}^{-2 k^{\prime} t}}{1 + \mathrm{e}^{-4 k^{\prime} t} - 2 \mathrm{e}^{-2 k^{\prime} t} \cos 4 \theta} \\
& = \frac{4 \sin^{2} 2 \theta}{\mathrm{e}^{2 k^{\prime} t} + \mathrm{e}^{-2 k^{\prime} t} - 2 \cos 4 \theta}
\end{aligned}
\]

Reflectance

\[
\begin{aligned}
1 - |T|^{2} & = 1 - \frac{4 \sin^{2} 2 \theta}{\mathrm{e}^{2 k^{\prime} t} + \mathrm{e}^{-2 k^{\prime} t} - 2 \cos 4 \theta} \\
& = \frac{\mathrm{e}^{2 k^{\prime} t} + \mathrm{e}^{-2 k^{\prime} t} - 2}{\mathrm{e}^{2 k^{\prime} t} + \mathrm{e}^{-2 k^{\prime} t} - 2 \cos 4 \theta}
\end{aligned}
\]

Where

\[
k^{\prime} = \sqrt{2mE} \sin \theta / \hbar
\]

Now \(H = \frac{e \hbar}{2 m c}\left( \sigma_{z} H_{z} + \sigma_{y} H_{y} \right)\)

$$
\begin{aligned}
\frac{\mathrm{d} \boldsymbol{\mu}}{\mathrm{d} t} & = \frac{1}{i \hbar}[\boldsymbol{\mu}, H] = \frac{1}{i \hbar}\left( \frac{e \hbar}{2 m c} \right)^{2}\left[ -\sigma_{x} \hat{x} - \sigma_{y} \hat{y} - \sigma_{z} \hat{z}, \sigma_{z} H_{z} + \sigma_{y} H_{y} \right] \\
& = \frac{1}{i \hbar}\left( \frac{e \hbar}{2 m c} \right)^{2}\left[ i\left( \sigma_{y} H_{z} - \sigma_{z} H_{y} \right) \hat{x} - i \sigma_{x} H_{z} \hat{y} + i \sigma_{x} H_{y} \hat{z} \right] \\
& = \frac{1}{i \hbar}\left( \frac{e \hbar}{2 m c} \right)^{2} \boldsymbol{\sigma} \times \boldsymbol{H} = \frac{e}{2 m c} \boldsymbol{H} \times \boldsymbol{\mu}
\end{aligned}
$$

Solving in the Cartesian coordinate system, take $B = B e_{z}$; the vector potential $A = \frac{1}{2}(B \times r) = \frac{1}{2}\left(-B y e_{x} + B x e_{y}\right)$, which is in the symmetric gauge, then the Hamiltonian operator of the system is

$$
\begin{aligned}
H & = \frac{1}{2 \mu}\left[\left(p_{x} + \frac{q B}{2} y\right)^{2} + \left(p_{y} - \frac{q B}{2} x\right)^{2} + p_{z}^{2}\right] + \frac{1}{2} \mu \omega_{0}^{2} r^{2} \\
& = \frac{p^{2}}{2 \mu} - \frac{q B}{2 \mu} L_{z} + \frac{q^{2} B^{2}}{8 \mu}(x^{2} + y^{2}) + \frac{1}{2} \mu \omega_{0}^{2} r^{2} \\
& = H_{1} + H_{2} - \omega L_{z}
\end{aligned}
$$

