problem:
Assume there are two identical non-interacting particles with spin $1/2$ in the same potential well. Find:

1. The two lowest possible total energy values of the two-particle system;
2. The degeneracy of each of these energy levels;
3. All possible two-particle wave functions corresponding to these energy levels (the spatial part expressed as $\psi$, and the spin part as $\left|S, M_{s}\right\rangle$, where $S$ is the total spin).

solution:
Therefore

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \chi_{0}(r)=2 \cos k r \tanh \frac{r}{a}+2 a k \sin k r \\
& \frac{1}{\chi_{0}} \cdot \frac{\mathrm{~d} \chi_{0}}{\mathrm{~d} r}=\frac{a k^{2} \cos k r-k \sin k r \tanh \frac{r}{a}+\frac{1}{a} \cos k r \operatorname{sech}^{2} \frac{r}{a}}{a k \sin k r+\cos k r \tanh \frac{r}{a}} \\
& \xrightarrow{r \rightarrow \infty} \frac{a k^{2} \cos k r-k \sin k r}{a k \sin k r+\cos k r}=k \frac{a k \cot k r-1}{\cot k r+a k}
\end{aligned}
$$

On the other hand, it is known that at infinity

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \chi_{0}(r)=\sin \left(k r+\delta_{0}\right) \\
& \frac{1}{\chi_{0}} \cdot \frac{\mathrm{~d} \chi_{0}}{\mathrm{~d} r}=k \cot \left(k r+\delta_{0}\right)=k \frac{\cot k r \cot \delta_{0}-1}{\cot k r+\cot \delta_{0}}
\end{aligned}
$$

By comparing the above two expressions, we get

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \cot \delta_{0}=a k \\
& \sin^{2} \delta_{0}=\frac{1}{1+\cot^{2} \delta_{0}}=\frac{1}{1+a^{2} k^{2}}
\end{aligned}
$$

The contribution of the s-wave to the total cross-section is

$$
\sigma_{t}=\frac{4 \pi}{k^{2}} \sin^{2} \delta_{0}=\frac{4 \pi}{k^{2}} \frac{1}{1+a^{2} k^{2}}=\frac{2 \pi \hbar^{2}}{m E} \frac{1}{1+\frac{2 a^{2} m E}{\hbar^{2}}}
$$

Introducing \( H^{\prime} = a \delta\left(x_{1}-x_{2}\right) \), the perturbative correction to the ground state energy is

\[
\begin{aligned}
\bar{H}^{\prime} &= \langle 11| H^{\prime}|11 \rangle \\
&= \int_{0}^{L} \int_{0}^{L} \mathrm{d} x_{1} \mathrm{d} x_{2} \, a \delta\left(x_{1}-x_{2}\right) \sin^{2}\left(\frac{\pi}{L} x_{1}\right) \sin^{2}\left(\frac{\pi}{L} x_{2}\right) \left(\frac{2}{L}\right)^{2} \\
&= a \left(\frac{2}{L}\right)^{2} \int_{0}^{L} \mathrm{d} x_{1} \sin^{4}\left(\frac{\pi}{L} x_{1}\right) = \frac{3a}{2L}
\end{aligned}
\]

The corrected ground state energy is

\[
E_{1,1}^{\prime} = E_{1,1} + \bar{H}^{\prime} = \frac{\hbar^{2} \pi^{2}}{m L^{2}} + \frac{3a}{2L}
\]

The contribution to the ground state energy due to the interaction is

\[
\begin{aligned}
\left\langle V_{\text{int}} \right\rangle & = \iint_{-\infty}^{\infty} \psi_0^*(x_1, x_2) V_{\text{int}}(x_1, x_2) \psi_0(x_1, x_2) \, \mathrm{d} x_1 \, \mathrm{d} x_2 \\
& = \frac{\alpha_0^2 \alpha}{\pi} \iint_{-\infty}^{\infty} \exp \left[-\alpha_0^2(x_1^2 + x_2^2) - \beta(x_1 - x_2)^2\right] \, \mathrm{d} x_1 \, \mathrm{d} x_2 \\
& = \frac{\alpha_0 \alpha}{(\alpha_0^2 + 2 \beta)^{1/2}}
\end{aligned}
\]

Consider the potential energy function as follows:

\[
V(x, y, z) = 
\begin{cases} 
0, & 0 < x < 2b, 0 < y < 2b, 0 < z < 2b \\ 
\infty, & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
\]

The zeroth-order wave function (inside the box) is

\[
\psi_{lmn}(x, y, z) = \sqrt{\frac{1}{b^3}} \sin \frac{l \pi x}{2b} \sin \frac{m \pi y}{2b} \sin \frac{n \pi z}{2b}
\]

Assuming \( E_{0} = E_{0} \hat{e}_{x} \), then \( H^{\prime} = -e E_{0} x e^{-\alpha t} \), so:

\[
\langle 111| x |211 \rangle = \frac{1}{b} \int_{0}^{2b} x \sin \frac{\pi x}{2b} \sin \frac{\pi x}{b} \, \mathrm{d}x = -\frac{32b}{9\pi^2}
\]

Therefore, the probability that the particle is in the state \(|211\rangle\) is

\[
\begin{aligned}
P &= \frac{1}{\hbar^2} \left| \int_{0}^{\infty} \langle 211 | H^{\prime} | 111 \rangle \exp \left( \frac{i \Delta E t}{\hbar} \right) \, \mathrm{d}t \right|^2 \\
\Delta E &= \frac{3 \pi^2 \hbar^2}{8mb^2} \\
P &= \left( \frac{32b e E_{0}}{9 \hbar \pi^2} \right)^2 \left| \int_{0}^{\infty} \exp \left( -\alpha t + i \frac{\Delta E t}{\hbar} \right) \, \mathrm{d}t \right|^2 \\
&= \left( \frac{32b e E_{0}}{9 \hbar \pi^2} \right)^2 \frac{\hbar^2}{\alpha^2 \hbar^2 + \Delta E^2}
\end{aligned}
\]

Let $\chi = rR$, where $R$ is the radial wave function, then we have  
$$  
\begin{array}{ll}  
\chi_{l}^{\prime \prime}(r) + \left[k^{2} - \frac{l(l+1)}{r^{2}}\right] \chi_{l}(r) = 0, & r > a, \quad k^{2} = \frac{2mE}{\hbar^{2}} \\  
\chi_{l}^{\prime \prime}(r) + \left[k^{\prime 2} - \frac{l(l+1)}{r^{2}}\right] \chi_{l}(r) = 0, & r < a \\  
k^{\prime 2} = \frac{2m(E + V_{0})}{\hbar^{2}}  
\end{array}  
$$  

Under the low-energy condition, calculate the s-wave partial wave, $l = 0$,  

$$  
\begin{array}{ll}  
\chi_{l}^{\prime \prime}(r) + k^{2} \chi_{l}(r) = 0, & r > a \\  
\chi_{l}^{\prime \prime}(r) + k^{\prime 2} \chi_{l}(r) = 0, & r < a  
\end{array}  
$$  

The solutions for the wave function are of the form  

$$  
\chi_{l}(r) =  
\begin{cases}  
A \sin \left(k^{\prime} r\right), & r < a \\  
A^{\prime} \sin \left(kr + \delta_{0}\right), & r > a  
\end{cases}  
$$  

The condition of continuity is that $\left(\ln \chi_{l}\right)^{\prime}$ is continuous at $r = a$, thus  

$$  
\begin{aligned}  
& k^{\prime} a \cot k^{\prime} a = k a \cot \left(k a + \delta_{0}\right) \\  
& \tan \left(k a + \delta_{0}\right) = \frac{k}{k^{\prime}} \tan k^{\prime} a \\  
& \delta_{0} = \arctan \left(\frac{k}{k^{\prime}} \tan k^{\prime} a \right) - k a  
\end{aligned}  
$$  

As $k \rightarrow 0, k^{\prime} \rightarrow k_{0} = \sqrt{\frac{2mV_{0}}{\hbar^{2}}}$  

$$  
\frac{k}{\tan \left(k a + \delta_{0}\right)} = \frac{k_{0}}{\tan k_{0} a}  
$$  

is a constant, so  

$$  
\begin{aligned}  
k a + \delta_{0} & \rightarrow 0 \\  
\tan \left(k a + \delta_{0}\right) & \approx k a + \delta_{0}  
\end{aligned}  
$$  

Therefore,  

$$  
\begin{aligned}  
\delta_{0} & \approx k a \left( \frac{\tan k_{0} a}{k_{0} a} - 1 \right) \\  
\sigma & \approx \frac{4 \pi}{k^{2}} \sin^{2} \delta_{0} \approx \frac{4 \pi}{k^{2}} \delta_{0}^{2} = 4 \pi a^{2} \left( \frac{\tan k_{0} a}{k_{0} a} - 1 \right)^{2}  
\end{aligned}  
$$  

When $k_{0} a \ll 1$  

$$  
\sigma \approx 4 \pi a^{2} \left[ \frac{1}{3}(k_{0} a)^{2} \right]^{2} = \frac{16 \pi a^{6} m^{2} V_{0}^{2}}{9 \hbar^{4}}  
$$

Assume the particle is incident along the $z$-direction, i.e., $k_{0}=k e_{z}$. In the lowest order Born approximation, the scattering amplitude is

$$
\begin{aligned}
f(\theta) & =-\frac{m}{2 \pi \hbar^{2}} \int \mathrm{e}^{\mathrm{i}\left(k_{0}-k\right) \cdot r}\left\langle x_{f} \right| A \sigma_{1} \cdot \sigma_{2} \left| x_{i} \right\rangle \frac{\mathrm{e}^{-\mu r^{\prime}}}{r^{\prime}} \mathrm{d}^{3} r^{\prime} \\
