solution:
The potential can be written as

\[
V(x)=
\begin{cases} 
0, & x \in [0, L] \\ 
\infty, & \text{elsewhere}
\end{cases}
\]

The single-particle spatial wave function for the system can be immediately written as

\[
\psi_{n}(x)= 
\begin{cases} 
\sqrt{\frac{2}{L}} \sin \frac{n \pi x}{L}, & x \in [0, L] \\ 
0, & \text{elsewhere}
\end{cases}
\]

The single-particle spin wave function is given by \( \binom{a}{b} \).\\
Since spin-dependent forces are not considered, the two-particle wave function can be factorized into the product of spatial and spin parts. The spin wave function is taken as the eigenstate of \( S^{2} = (S_{1} + S_{2})^{2} \) and \( S_{z} = S_{1z} + S_{2z} \)

\[
\begin{aligned}
& \chi_{JM} = \chi_{JM} \\
& S^{2} \chi_{JM} = J(J+1) \chi_{JM} \\
& S_{z} \chi_{JM} = M \chi_{JM}
\end{aligned}
\]

For \( J = 0 \), it is a spin singlet state, which is antisymmetric under particle exchange. For \( J = 1 \), it is a spin triplet state, which is symmetric under particle exchange.\\
The spatial wave function can also be symmetrized and antisymmetrized

\[
\begin{aligned}
& \psi_{nm}^{A}(x_{1}, x_{2}) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \left[\psi_{n}(x_{1}) \psi_{m}(x_{2}) - \psi_{n}(x_{2}) \psi_{m}(x_{1})\right] \\
& \psi_{nm}^{S}(x_{1}, x_{2}) = 
\begin{cases} 
\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \left[\psi_{n}(x_{1}) \psi_{m}(x_{2}) + \psi_{n}(x_{2}) \psi_{m}(x_{1})\right], & n \neq m \\ 
\psi_{n}(x_{1}) \psi_{n}(x_{2}), & n = m
\end{cases}
\end{aligned}
\]

So the total wave function can be written as

\[
\begin{aligned}
& \psi_{nm}^{A}(x_{1}, x_{2}) \chi_{JM}^{S} \\
& \psi_{nm}^{S}(x_{1}, x_{2}) \chi_{JM}^{A}
\end{aligned}
\]

The corresponding energy is

\[
E = \frac{\hbar^{2} \pi^{2}}{2mL^{2}}(n^{2} + m^{2}), \quad n, m = 1, 2, \ldots
\]

(i) Ground state. \( n = m = 1 \).\\
The spatial wave function is symmetric, so the spin must be a singlet

\[
\psi_{0} = \psi_{11}^{S}(x_{1}, x_{2}) \chi_{00}
\]

(ii) First excited state. \( n = 1, m = 2 \).

\[
\psi_{1} = 
\begin{cases} 
\psi_{12}^{A}(x_{1}, x_{2}) \chi_{1M}, & M = 0, \pm 1 \\ 
\psi_{12}^{S}(x_{1}, x_{2}) \chi_{00} 
\end{cases}
\]

Fourfold degeneracy.\\
(iii) Second excited state. \( n = 2, m = 2 \).

The spatial wave function is symmetric, so the spin must be a singlet

\[
\psi_{2} = \psi_{22}^{S}(x_{1}, x_{2}) \chi_{00}
\]

Non-degenerate.

The probability of finding the system in the \(k\) state is given by

\[
