(2) Noting that \( H^{\prime} \) does not alter the spin, after adding the magnetic field, we can use the following neutron-antineutron representation:

\[
\mathrm{n} \uparrow \sim \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}, \quad \overline{\mathrm{n}} \uparrow \sim \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}, \quad \mathrm{n} \downarrow \sim \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 1 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}, \quad \overline{\mathrm{n}} \downarrow \sim \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}
\]

Thus, the matrix elements of the perturbed Hamiltonian are

\[
\begin{pmatrix}
-\mu_{\mathrm{n}} B_{0} & \varepsilon & 0 & 0 \\
\varepsilon & -\mu_{\mathrm{n}} B_{0} & 0 & 0 \\
0 & 0 & \mu_{\mathrm{n}} B_{0} & \varepsilon \\
0 & 0 & \varepsilon & \mu_{\mathrm{n}} B_{0}
\end{pmatrix}
\]

Where

\[
\mu_{\mathrm{n}} \approx -6 \times 10^{-18} \text{ MeV/Gs}, \quad \mu_{\mathrm{n}} \approx 6 \times 10^{-18} \text{ MeV/Gs}
\]

It is easy to see the eigenvalue equation can be divided into two equations (where \(\mu_{\mathrm{n}}\) is replaced by \(-\mu_{\mathrm{n}}\))

\[
\begin{aligned}
&\begin{pmatrix} -\mu_{\mathrm{n}} B_{0} - E^{(1)} & \varepsilon \\ \varepsilon & \mu_{\mathrm{n}} B_{0} - E^{(1)} \end{pmatrix} \binom{a \uparrow}{b \uparrow} = 0 \\
&\begin{pmatrix} \mu_{\mathrm{n}} B_{0} - E^{(1)} & \varepsilon \\ \varepsilon & -\mu_{\mathrm{n}} B_{0} - E^{(1)} \end{pmatrix} \binom{a \downarrow}{b \downarrow} = 0
\end{aligned}
\]

Solving this, we obtain

\[
\begin{gathered}
E_{\pm}^{(1)} = \pm \lambda = \pm \sqrt{\varepsilon^{2} + (\mu_{\mathrm{n}} B_{0})^{2}} \\
\binom{a \uparrow}{b \uparrow}_{+} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2 \lambda}} \binom{\sqrt{\lambda - \mu_{\mathrm{n}} B_{0}}}{\sqrt{\lambda + \mu_{\mathrm{n}} B_{0}}}, \quad \binom{a \uparrow}{b \uparrow}_{-} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2 \lambda}} \binom{\sqrt{\lambda + \mu_{\mathrm{n}} B_{0}}}{-\sqrt{\lambda - \mu_{\mathrm{n}} B_{0}}} \\
\binom{a \downarrow}{b \downarrow}_{+} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2 \lambda}} \binom{\sqrt{\lambda + \mu_{\mathrm{n}} B_{0}}}{\sqrt{\lambda - \mu_{\mathrm{n}} B_{0}}}, \quad \binom{a \downarrow}{b \downarrow}_{-} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2 \lambda}} \binom{\sqrt{\lambda - \mu_{\mathrm{n}} B_{0}}}{-\sqrt{\lambda + \mu_{\mathrm{n}} B_{0}}}
\end{gathered}
\]

At \( t=0 \), the system is in the neutron state

\[
\begin{aligned}
& \mathrm{n} \uparrow \sim \sqrt{\frac{\lambda - \mu_{\mathrm{n}} B_{0}}{2 \lambda}} \binom{a \uparrow}{b \uparrow}_{+} + \sqrt{\frac{\lambda + \mu_{\mathrm{n}} B_{0}}{2 \lambda}} \binom{a \uparrow}{b \uparrow}_{-} \\
& \mathrm{n} \downarrow \sim \sqrt{\frac{\lambda + \mu_{\mathrm{n}} B_{0}}{2 \lambda}} \binom{a \downarrow}{b \downarrow}_{+} + \sqrt{\frac{\lambda - \mu_{\mathrm{n}} B_{0}}{2 \lambda}} \binom{a \downarrow}{b \downarrow}_{-}
\end{aligned}
\]

The state at any time \( t \) is

\[
\begin{aligned}
& (\uparrow) \sim e^{-\mathrm{i} m_{\mathrm{n}} c t / \hbar} \frac{1}{2 \lambda} \binom{(\lambda - \mu_{\mathrm{n}} B_{0}) e^{-\mathrm{i} \lambda t / \hbar} + (\lambda + \mu_{\mathrm{n}} B_{0}) e^{\mathrm{i} \lambda t / \hbar}}{\sqrt{\lambda^{2} - (\mu_{\mathrm{n}} B_{0})^{2}} (e^{-\mathrm{i} \lambda t / \hbar} - e^{\mathrm{i} \lambda t / \hbar})} \\
& (\downarrow) \sim e^{-\mathrm{i} m_{\mathrm{n}} c t / \hbar} \frac{1}{2 \lambda} \binom{(\lambda + \mu_{\mathrm{n}} B_{0}) e^{-\mathrm{i} \lambda t / \hbar} + (\lambda - \mu_{\mathrm{n}} B_{0}) e^{\mathrm{i} \lambda t / \hbar}}{\sqrt{\lambda^{2} - (\mu_{\mathrm{n}} B_{0})^{2}} (e^{-\mathrm{i} \lambda t / \hbar} - e^{\mathrm{i} \lambda t / \hbar})}
\end{aligned}
\]

Thus, the probability for \( \mathrm{n} \uparrow \rightarrow \overline{\mathrm{n}} \uparrow \) is

\[
\begin{aligned}
P_{\mathrm{n} \uparrow \rightarrow \overline{\mathrm{n}}}(t) & = \frac{\varepsilon^{2}}{\lambda^{2}} \sin^{2} \frac{\lambda t}{\hbar} \\
& = \frac{\varepsilon^{2}}{\varepsilon^{2} + (\mu_{\mathrm{n}} B_{0})^{2}} \sin^{2} \frac{\sqrt{\varepsilon^{2} + (\mu_{\mathrm{n}} B_{0})^{2}} t}{\hbar}
\end{aligned}
\]

And for \( n \downarrow \rightarrow \overline{\mathrm{n}} \downarrow \) the probability is

\[
\begin{aligned}
P_{\mathrm{n} \downarrow \rightarrow \overline{\mathrm{n}}}(t) & = \frac{\varepsilon^{2}}{\lambda^{2}} \sin^{2} \frac{\lambda t}{\hbar} \\
& = \frac{\varepsilon^{2}}{\varepsilon^{2} + (\mu_{\mathrm{n}} B_{0})^{2}} \sin^{2} \frac{\sqrt{\varepsilon^{2} + (\mu_{\mathrm{n}} B_{0})^{2}} t}{\hbar}
\end{aligned}
\]

Finally, if the neutron is unpolarized, then the probability for \( \mathrm{n} \rightarrow \overline{\mathrm{n}} \) is

\[
\begin{aligned}
P(t) & = \frac{1}{2} P_{\mathrm{n} \uparrow \rightarrow \overline{\mathrm{n}} \uparrow}(t) + \frac{1}{2} P_{\mathrm{n} \downarrow \rightarrow \overline{\mathrm{n}} \downarrow}(t) \\
& = \frac{\varepsilon^{2}}{\varepsilon^{2} + (\mu_{\mathrm{n}} B_{0})^{2}} \sin^{2} \frac{\sqrt{\varepsilon^{2} + (\mu_{\mathrm{n}} B_{0})^{2}} t}{\hbar}
\end{aligned}
\]

Polarization does not affect the probability.

From the data given, it is known that \(\mu_{\mathrm{n}} B_{0} \gg \varepsilon\),

\[
P(t) \leq \left( \frac{1.65 \times 10^{-28}}{6 \times 10^{-18} \times \frac{1}{2}} \right)^{2} \approx 0.3 \times 10^{-20}
\]

One can see that the transition probability is extremely small.

**Solution Method 1:** When \( x < 0 \), the wave function remains in the form as in equation (1). For \( 0 < x < t \), the Schrödinger equation is

\[
-\frac{\hbar^{2}}{2m} \nabla^{2} \psi = 0
\]

If \( \psi \) takes the form: \( \mathrm{e}^{\mathrm{i} k_{y} \cdot y} \cdot \mathrm{e}^{k x} \), then

\[
-k^{\prime 2} + k^{2} = 0, \quad k = \pm k^{\prime}
\]

Thus, the wave function for \( 0 < x < t \) is

\[
\psi_{2}(x, y) = \left(a \mathrm{e}^{k^{\prime} x} + b \mathrm{e}^{-k^{\prime} x}\right) \mathrm{e}^{i k_{y} \cdot y}
\]

Overall, we have

\[
\begin{array}{ll}
x < 0, & \psi_{1}(x) = \mathrm{e}^{\mathrm{i} k_{x} x} + r \mathrm{e}^{-\mathrm{i} k_{x} x} \\
0 < x < t, & \psi_{2}(x) = a \mathrm{e}^{k^{\prime} x} + b \mathrm{e}^{-k^{\prime} x} \\
x > t, & \psi_{3}(x) = c \mathrm{e}^{\mathrm{i} k_{x} x}
\end{array}
\]

Where

\[
k_{x} = \sqrt{\frac{2mE}{\hbar^{2}}} \cos \theta, \quad k^{\prime} = \sqrt{\frac{2mE}{\hbar^{2}}} \sin \theta
\]

Only the \( x \) component is written here. The \( y \) component is simply \( \mathrm{e}^{\mathrm{i} k_{y} \cdot y} \).

\[
k_{y} = \sqrt{\frac{2mE}{\hbar^{2}}} \sin \theta
\]

All boundary conditions are

\[
\begin{gathered}
\left\{
\begin{array}{l}
1+r = a+b \\
\mathrm{i} k_{x}(1-r) = k^{\prime}(a-b) \\
c \mathrm{e}^{\mathrm{i} k_{x} t} = a \mathrm{e}^{k^{\prime} t} + b \mathrm{e}^{-k^{\prime} t}
\end{array}
\right. \\
\mathrm{i} k_{x} \cdot c \mathrm{e}^{\mathrm{i} k_{x} t} = k^{\prime} a \mathrm{e}^{k^{\prime} t} - k^{\prime} b \mathrm{e}^{-k^{\prime} t}
\end{gathered}
\]

Solving, we have

\[
\begin{gathered}
r = \frac{\mathrm{e}^{2 k^{\prime} t} - 1}{1 - \beta^{2} \mathrm{e}^{2 k^{\prime} t}}, \quad \beta = \frac{k^{\prime} - \mathrm{i} k_{x}}{k^{\prime} + \mathrm{i} k_{x}} \\
|R|^{2} = |r|^{2} = \frac{\mathrm{e}^{2 k^{\prime} t} + \mathrm{e}^{-2 k^{\prime} t} - 2}{\mathrm{e}^{2 k^{\prime} t} + \mathrm{e}^{-2 k^{\prime} t} - 2 \cos 4 \theta}
\end{gathered}
\]

**Solution Method 2:** The problem can also be solved by using the method of amplitude superposition, similar to the case of a Fabry-Perot interferometer in optics.

Only considering the \( x \) component, let \( T_{12}, R_{12} \) represent the amplitude transmission and reflection coefficients for the wave from medium 1 to medium 2 respectively. Let \( T_{21}, R_{21} \) represent the amplitude transmission and reflection coefficients for the wave from medium 2 to medium 1 respectively. Given that the incident wave amplitude is 1, the amplitude of the wave emerging from medium 2 is

\[
\begin{aligned}
T & = T_{12} \mathrm{e}^{-\delta} \cdot T_{21} + T_{12} \mathrm{e}^{-\delta} \cdot R_{21} \mathrm{e}^{-2\delta} R_{21} \cdot T_{21} + T_{12} \mathrm{e}^{-\delta} \cdot \left(R_{21} \mathrm{e}^{-2\delta} R_{21}\right)^{2} \cdot T_{21} + \cdots \\
& = T_{12} \mathrm{e}^{-\delta} T_{21} \left[1 + R_{21}^{2} \mathrm{e}^{-2\delta} + \left(R_{21}^{2} \mathrm{e}^{-2\delta}\right)^{2} + \cdots\right] = T_{12} T_{21} \mathrm{e}^{-\delta} \frac{1}{1 - R_{21}^{2} \mathrm{e}^{-2\delta}}
\end{aligned}
\]

Where \( \mathrm{e}^{-\delta} \) is the attenuation coefficient of the wave traveling from one interface to the other in medium 2.

\[
\delta = k^{\prime} t, \quad k^{\prime} = \sqrt{2mE(1 - \cos^{2} \theta)} / \hbar = \sqrt{2mE} \sin \theta / \hbar
\]

Using the result from (1)

\[
R_{12} = \left(k_{1 x} - k_{2 x}\right) / \left(k_{1 x} + k_{2 x}\right), \quad T_{12} = 1 + R_{12} = 2 k_{1} / \left(k_{1 x} + k_{2 x}\right)
\]

However,

\[
\begin{aligned}
& k_{1 x} = \sqrt{2mE} \cos \theta / \hbar \\
& k_{2 x} = \mathrm{i} k^{\prime} = \mathrm{i} \sqrt{2mE} \sin \theta / \hbar
\end{aligned}
\]

So,

\[
\begin{aligned}
& T_{12} = \frac{2 k_{1 x}}{k_{1 x} + k_{2 x}} = \frac{2 \cos \theta}{\cos \theta + \mathrm{i} \sin \theta} = 2 \cos \theta \mathrm{e}^{-\mathrm{i} \theta} \\
& T_{21} = \frac{2 k_{2 x}}{k_{1 x} + k_{2 x}} = \frac{2 \sin \theta}{\cos \theta + \mathrm{i} \sin \theta} = 2 \mathrm{i} \sin \theta \mathrm{e}^{-\mathrm{i} \theta}
\end{aligned}
\]

\[
R_{21} = \frac{k_{2 x} - k_{1 x}}{k_{1 x} + k_{2 x}} = \frac{\mathrm{i} \sin \theta - \cos \theta}{\mathrm{i} \sin \theta + \cos \theta} = \mathrm{e}^{-2 \mathrm{i} \theta}
\]

Thus,

\[
\begin{aligned}
T & = T_{12} T_{21} \mathrm{e}^{-\delta} \frac{1}{1 - R_{21}^{2} \mathrm{e}^{-2\delta}} \\
& = \frac{4 \mathrm{i} \cos \theta \sin \theta \mathrm{e}^{-2 \mathrm{i} \theta} \cdot \mathrm{e}^{-k^{\prime} t}}{1 - \mathrm{e}^{-4 \mathrm{i} \theta} \mathrm{e}^{-2 k^{\prime} t}} \\
& = \frac{2 \mathrm{i} \sin 2 \theta \mathrm{e}^{-2 \mathrm{i} \theta} \mathrm{e}^{-k^{\prime} t}}{1 - \mathrm{e}^{-4 \mathrm{i} \theta} \mathrm{e}^{-2 k^{\prime} t}}
\end{aligned}
\]

Transmittance

\[
\begin{aligned}
|T|^{2} & = \frac{4 \sin^{2} 2 \theta \mathrm{e}^{-2 k^{\prime} t}}{\left(1 - \mathrm{e}^{-2 k^{\prime} t} \cos 4 \theta\right)^{2} + \left(\mathrm{e}^{-2 k^{\prime} t} \sin 4 \theta\right)^{2}} \\
& = \frac{4 \sin^{2} 2 \theta \mathrm{e}^{-2 k^{\prime} t}}{1 + \mathrm{e}^{-4 k^{\prime} t} - 2 \mathrm{e}^{-2 k^{\prime} t} \cos 4 \theta} \\
& = \frac{4 \sin^{2} 2 \theta}{\mathrm{e}^{2 k^{\prime} t} + \mathrm{e}^{-2 k^{\prime} t} - 2 \cos 4 \theta}
\end{aligned}
\]

Reflectance

\[
\begin{aligned}
1 - |T|^{2} & = 1 - \frac{4 \sin^{2} 2 \theta}{\mathrm{e}^{2 k^{\prime} t} + \mathrm{e}^{-2 k^{\prime} t} - 2 \cos 4 \theta} \\
& = \frac{\mathrm{e}^{2 k^{\prime} t} + \mathrm{e}^{-2 k^{\prime} t} - 2}{\mathrm{e}^{2 k^{\prime} t} + \mathrm{e}^{-2 k^{\prime} t} - 2 \cos 4 \theta}
\end{aligned}
\]

Where

\[
k^{\prime} = \sqrt{2mE} \sin \theta / \hbar
\]

In the center-of-mass frame, the two particles are completely symmetric. This is equivalent to having a fixed center of force at the midpoint of the line joining the two particles, described by

$$
V(\rho)=e^{2} \frac{\mathrm{e}^{-2 \lambda \rho}}{2 \rho}
$$

where $\rho = r / 2$ is half the distance between the two particles. Because the incident energy is very high, we can use the Born approximation. The first Born approximation result is

$$
\begin{aligned}
f(\theta) & =-\frac{m}{2 \pi \hbar^{2}} \int \mathrm{e}^{-\mathrm{i} q \cdot \rho} V(\rho) \mathrm{d}^{3} \rho \\
& =-\frac{2 m}{\hbar^{2} q} \int_{0}^{\infty} \mathrm{d} \rho \frac{e^{2}}{2} \mathrm{e}^{-2 \lambda \rho} \sin q \rho \\
& =-\frac{m e^{2}}{\hbar^{2}\left[q^{2}+(2 \lambda)^{2}\right]}
\end{aligned}
$$

where $q$ is the change in momentum of the particle before and after scattering, given by $q=2 k \sin \frac{\theta}{2}$. Considering the symmetry issues of the wave function in the system of identical particles:

$$
\left.\begin{array}{ll}
\text{For } S=0 \text{ state, } \quad \sigma_{s}(\theta) & =|f(\theta)+f(\pi-\theta)|^{2}, \\
\text{For } S=1 \text{ state, } & \sigma_{a}(\theta)
\end{array}=|f(\theta)-f(\pi-\theta)|^{2} .\right]
$$

$$
\begin{aligned}
\sigma_{a}(\theta) & =\frac{1}{4}\left(\frac{m e^{2}}{\hbar^{2}}\right)^{2}\left[\frac{k^{2} \cos \theta}{\left(k^{2} \sin^{2} \frac{\theta}{2}+\lambda^{2}\right)\left(k^{2} \cos^{2} \frac{\theta}{2}+\lambda^{2}\right)}\right]^{2} \\
\sigma_{t} & =\frac{1}{4} \sigma_{s}+\frac{3}{4} \sigma_{a} \\
& =\frac{1}{16}\left(\frac{m e^{2}}{\hbar^{2}}\right)^{2} \frac{\left(k^{2}+2 \lambda^{2}\right)^{2}+3\left(k^{2} \cos \theta\right)^{2}}{\left[\left(k^{2} \sin^{2} \frac{\theta}{2}+\lambda^{2}\right)\left(k^{2} \cos^{2} \frac{\theta}{2}+\lambda^{2}\right)\right]^{2}}
\end{aligned}
$$

