\end{equation*}

Equation (4) can then be written as:

\begin{equation*}
\ddot{\boldsymbol{r}}+\omega_{0}^{2} \boldsymbol{r}+2 \delta \dot{\boldsymbol{r}}=\frac{e}{m} \boldsymbol{E}_{0} e^{-\mathrm{i} \omega t} \tag{6}
\end{equation*}

where $\omega_{0}=\sqrt{\frac{k}{m}}$ is the "natural" frequency of electron oscillation within an atom (or molecule), $\delta=g / 2m$ is the damping coefficient, and $\boldsymbol{E}_{0}$ is the amplitude of the electric field in the electromagnetic wave.

We assume that the solution to equation (6) has the following form:

\begin{equation*}
\boldsymbol{r}=\boldsymbol{r}_{0} e^{-\mathrm{i} \omega t} \tag{7}
\end{equation*}

where $\boldsymbol{r}_{0}$ is the amplitude of the electron displacement. Substituting equation (7) into equation (6) and performing the necessary differentiation, we obtain:

\begin{equation*}
