The relationship between the dielectric constant and the susceptibility of the medium is given by

\begin{equation*}
\varepsilon=1+\alpha \tag{13}
\end{equation*}

Substituting equation (12) into equation (13), we obtain

\begin{equation*}
\varepsilon=1+\frac{e^{2} N}{\varepsilon_{0} m\left(\omega_{0}^{2}-\omega^{2} - 2\mathrm{i} \delta \omega\right)} \tag{14}
\end{equation*}

On the other hand, $n=\sqrt{\varepsilon}$, where $n$ is the refractive index of the medium. Therefore, equation (14) takes the following form:

\begin{equation*}
n^{2}=1+\frac{e^{2} N}{\varepsilon_{0} m\left(\omega_{0}^{2}-\omega^{2} - 2\mathrm{i} \delta \omega\right)} \tag{15}
\end{equation*}

Estimates suggest that the second term in equation (15) is small compared to 1. In this case, equation (15) can be written as

\begin{equation*}
n=1+\frac{e^{2} N}{2 \varepsilon_{0} m\left(\omega_{0}^{2}-\omega^{2} - 2\mathrm{i} \delta \omega\right)} \tag{16}
\end{equation*}

The refractive index we seek is a complex quantity, given by

\begin{equation*}
n=n^{\prime}+\mathrm{i} n^{\prime \prime} \tag{17}
\end{equation*}

where $n^{\prime}, n^{\prime \prime}$ are the real and imaginary parts of the complex refractive index, respectively.

From equation (16), we find the real part of the refractive index to be

\begin{equation*}
n^{\prime}=1+\frac{e^{2} N\left(\omega_{0}^{2}-\omega^{2}\right)}{2 \varepsilon_{0} m\left(\omega_{0}^{2}-\omega^{2} + 4 \delta^{2} \omega^{2}\right)} \tag{18}
\end{equation*}

It is well known that the imaginary part of the complex refractive index describes the attenuation of the electromagnetic wave within the medium. The graph of the function $n(\omega)$ is shown in the figure. The region near the natural (resonant) frequency $\omega_{0}$ is referred to as the "anomalous dispersion" region.

From the conservation of momentum, we know that the sum of the momentum components perpendicular to the direction of the photon's incidence is zero. Therefore,

$$
\begin{gathered}
\boldsymbol{p}_{f}=\boldsymbol{p}_{e}+\boldsymbol{p}_{f^{\prime}} \\
p_{s} \sin \theta=p_{f^{\prime}}, \quad p_{c} \cos \theta=p_{f}
\end{gathered}
$$

where

$$
\begin{gathered}
p_{e}=m v, \quad p_{f}=\frac{h f}{c}, \quad p_{f^{\prime}}=\frac{h f^{\prime}}{c} \\
\tan \theta=\frac{h f^{\prime} / c}{h f / c}=\frac{f^{\prime}}{f}
\end{gathered}
$$

